          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Sandhi: Introduction",
        "topic_summary": "Euphonic sound combination rules.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_sandhi_intro",
            "summary": "An introduction to Sandhi, the rules governing sound changes when words or morphemes meet, crucial for reading and understanding texts."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Nouns (Nāma)",
        "topic_summary": "Naming words, substantives.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_nouns",
            "summary": "Understanding nouns (nāmapadam) as words that name persons, places, things, or ideas, and their grammatical properties."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Gender (Liṅgam)",
        "topic_summary": "Masculine, Feminine, Neuter.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_gender",
            "summary": "The concept of grammatical gender in Sanskrit (Pum̐liṅga, Strīliṅga, Napuṃsakaliṅga) and how it affects noun and adjective forms."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Number (Vacanam)",
        "topic_summary": "Singular, Dual, Plural.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_number",
            "summary": "The three grammatical numbers in Sanskrit: Ekavacanam (singular), Dvivacanam (dual), and Bahuvacanam (plural)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Cases (Vibhakti)",
        "topic_summary": "Noun roles in sentence.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_cases",
            "summary": "Introduction to the eight cases (vibhaktis) that indicate a noun's grammatical function in a sentence (e.g., subject, object, instrument)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Declension: 'a'-stems (Masc.)",
        "topic_summary": "Noun ending patterns.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_decl_a_masc",
            "summary": "Learning the declension patterns for masculine nouns ending in short 'a' (e.g., rāma - Rama)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Declension: 'ā'-stems (Fem.)",
        "topic_summary": "Feminine noun endings.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_decl_aa_fem",
            "summary": "Learning the declension patterns for feminine nouns ending in long 'ā' (e.g., sītā - Sita)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Pronouns: Personal",
        "topic_summary": "I, you, he/she/it.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_pronouns_personal",
            "summary": "Introduction to personal pronouns (asmad - I/we, yuṣmad - you, tad - he/she/it/they) and their declensions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Verbs (Kriyā)",
        "topic_summary": "Action or state words.",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "type": "topic_definition",
            "id": "sanskrit_topic_verbs",
